This study illustrates the physical state of Chicago and how it has evolved since mid-2000s. It also explores relationships between the physical evolution and economic development, looking for potential links between urban blight, new construction, and business activity.

Urban blight is predominantly affecting areas in the South and West parts of Chicago, as shown on the map above. Notably, there is not much overlap between concentrations of vacant and abandoned buildings and economic activity, as measured by newly-issued business licenses.

blight_summary <- read.csv("blight_summary.csv")
comm_crosswalk <- read_csv("comm_crosswalk.csv") 

blight_summary <- 
  left_join(blight_summary, comm_crosswalk, by = c("comm" = "comm_number"))

blight_summary_highlight <- 
  filter(blight_summary, comm %in% c("67","68","25", "49", "69", "46", "71", "61", "53", "29"))

(time_series_blight <- ggplot(blight_summary) +
  geom_line(data = blight_summary, mapping = aes(x = year, y = n, group = as.character(comm)), color = "#4F8282") +
    geom_line(data = blight_summary_highlight, mapping = aes(x = year, y = n, group = as.character(comm)), color = "#680A4D") +
  theme_evelina +
  labs(x = "", y = "\nNumber of buildings reported \nas vacant or abandoned", 
       title = "\nUrban blight is concentrated and persistent",
       subtitle = "A handful of community areas account for disproportionate share of \nChicago's urban blight. The leaders of the ranking have not changed \nsince 2011, are in South and West of the city",
       caption = "Source: 311 Service Requests, 2018, City of Chicago Data Portal") +
    geom_label_repel(data = filter(blight_summary_highlight, year == 2011), mapping = aes(x = year, y = n, label = comm_name_norm), fill = "#EBF1DE", family = "Bodoni MT"))

ggsave("time_series_blight.png", height = 9, width = 7)

Analysis of urban blight over time reveals an important insight: most of community areas that had lots of blight reported in 2010 and 2011 continued to lead the ranking of affected areas all the way through 2018. At the same time, it looks like the problem has become less urgent as the city recovers from the Great Recession - nearly all of the community areas had urban blight declining since the 2011 peak.

permit_cost <- permits_comms_summary %>%
  filter(year <= 2018 & year >= 2014 & area != 0) %>%
  group_by(large_area, area, comm_name) %>%
  summarize(npermits = n(), cost = round(sum(ESTIMATED_COST) / 1000000000, 2))

joined2 <- left_join(joined, blight1418_sum, by = "comm_number") %>%
  left_join(pop_chi, by = c("comm_name"= "community")) %>%
  mutate(npermits_norm = npermits / TOT_POP, 
         cost_norm = cost*1000000000 / TOT_POP,
         blight_norm = blight / TOT_POP, 
         blight_norm_hip = 1/blight_norm)

    annotate(geom = "text", x = 1300, y = 1.5, label = "Areas disproportionately affected by\nblight are not seeing much new construction. \nAmong them: West Englewood,Englewood, Roseland, \nAuburn Gresham, Greater Grand Crossing", family = "Bodoni MT", size = 3, hjust = 0) +

joined2 %>% select(comm_name, blight, cost) %>% filter(blight>=500 & cost <= 1) %>% arrange(desc(blight))

summary(lm(formula = cost_norm ~ blight_norm + blight_norm_hip, data = joined2))

Most of community areas in Chicago area are relatively low both on blight and new construction. If we take a closer look, however, it becomes apparent that construction is booming in the areas with minimal blight and is not happening in the areas disproportionately affected by blight.

The negative relationship between new construction activity and existing urban blight might explain persistence of urban blight in certain areas that we saw on the previous chart.

(construction_facets <- permits_comms_summary %>%
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) %>%
  filter(year >= 2006 & year <= 2018 & area != 0) %>%
  group_by(year, area) %>%
  summarize(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(year1 = as.character(year)) %>%
  ggplot() +    
  geom_rect(aes(xmin="2008", xmax="2009", ymin=0, ymax=2500), fill= "#680A4D", alpha=0.005) +
  geom_area(mapping = aes(x = year1, y = n), group = 1, fill = "#2C9191", alpha = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~area, ncol = 3) +
  theme_evelina +
     labs(x = "", y = "\nNew construction and renovation permits", 
       title = "\nConstruction activity varies across the city",
       subtitle = "The number of permits issued in Chicago for new construction, renovations \nfell in the wake of the Great Recession but bounced back \nto pre-recession level by 2018",
       caption = "Source: Building Permits, Chicago Data Portal, City of Chicago") +
    scale_x_discrete(breaks = c("2006", "2008", "2010", "2012", "2014", "2016", "2018"),
                                labels = c("2006", "2008", "2010", "2012", "2014", "2016", "2018")) +
    theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 7)))

ggsave("construction_facets.png", width = 8, height = 7)

There is substantial heterogeneity in construction activity by city area. Central business district, West side and North side have had construction booming for the last several years, while areas further away from downtown have seen development on a lower scale. Notably, construction activity - as measured in building permits for new construction and renovations - plummeted in the wake of the Great Recession but has practically bounced back up to the pre-recession level across the city.

Looking at number of building permits in combination with the estimated construction costs allows us to see a more colorful picture. For example, we now see that even though there were more permits issued in Near North Side, more funds were invested in construction in Near West Side in 2018. Similarly, we notice that Woodlawn boasts high investment despite being far from the top by the number of permits issued. This may be explained by several large University of Chicago projects underway in the area.

It looks like in the last five years, construction investment has been shifting from the Loop and Near North Side - the central business district and the adjacent area hosting some of the key tourist attractions and entertanment establishments - to the neighbourhoods around them, especially to the north and west. The place of O’Hare in the ranking decreased, reflecting no significant recent investments in the airport.

biz <- read.csv("biz.csv")

#turn into spatial points dataframe
biz_map <- biz %>% drop_na(LONGITUDE) %>%
  mutate(app_type = APPLICATION.TYPE,
         term_start_date = LICENSE.TERM.START.DATE, biz_act = BUSINESS.ACTIVITY, license_descr = LICENSE.DESCRIPTION)

coordinates(biz_map) <- c("LONGITUDE", "LATITUDE") 

#read in shapefiles
comm_shapes <- readOGR(".", "comm_shapes")

proj4string(biz_map) <- proj4string(comm_shapes)

# combine is.na() with over() to do the containment test
inside.comm <- !is.na(over(biz_map, as(comm_shapes, "SpatialPolygons")))

biz_map$comm_name <- over(biz_map, comm_shapes)$community

biz_comms <- as.data.frame(biz_map) %>%
  select(ID, LONGITUDE, LATITUDE, comm_name, CITY, license_descr, biz_act,
         app_type, term_start_date,
         year, SSA) %>%
  filter(CITY %in% c("CHICAGO", "CHIICAGO", 
                     "CHICAGP", "CHCIAGO", "CHCAGO")) %>%
  filter(app_type %in% c("ISSUE", "C_LOC"))

biz_comms_decade <- biz_comms %>%

  filter(year %in% c("2008", "2013", "2018")) %>%

  group_by(year, large_area, area) %>%
  summarize(nlicenses_area = sum(nlicenses)) %>%
  spread(key = year, value = nlicenses_area) %>%
  #gather(key = "year", value = "nlicenses_area", "2008":"2018") %>%
  drop_na(area)

The number of applications for business licenses has fallen in Chicago across the board from 2008 to 2018. One reason could be a recent business license reform that took place in 2013, reducing the number of businesses that needed licenses to operate.

At the same time, it is apparent that there is significant heterogeneity among different parts of the city. Once again - now in terms of business licenses - we see the bulk of economic activity happenning downtown but gradually shifting from the very central part of Chicago to its immediate surroundings, especially in the West.

Notably, license applications by new food and drinks serving establishments followed a pattern in many ways similar to that of the new construction permits. While it is hard to infer which one causes the other, it looks like construction and restaurant industry move together - both resulting from and further boosting attractiveness of the areas where they spread. In the last 15 years in Chicago, new restaurants and bars have increasingly opened in the areas to the North and West of the Loop - central business district - that have now achieved parity or nearly parity in concentration with the latter.

cormat <- round(cor(pre_corr_matrix1), 2) 

reorder_cormat <- function(cormat){
# Use correlation between variables as distance
dd <- as.dist((1-cormat)/2)
hc <- hclust(dd)
cormat <-cormat[hc$order, hc$order]
}

cormat <- reorder_cormat(cormat)

# Get lower triangle of the correlation matrix
  get_lower_tri<-function(cormat){
    cormat[upper.tri(cormat)] <- NA
    return(cormat)
  }
  # Get upper triangle of the correlation matrix
  get_upper_tri <- function(cormat){
    cormat[lower.tri(cormat)]<- NA
    return(cormat)
  }
lower_tri <- get_lower_tri(cormat)  
  
melted_corr <- melt(lower_tri, na.rm = TRUE) %>% 
  filter(Var1 != "year" & Var2 != "year")

(tiles_corr_by_industry <- ggplot() +
  geom_tile(data = melted_corr, 
            mapping = aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = value), color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(high = "#005A5B", mid = "#EBF1DE") +
  theme_evelina +  
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(), 
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.35),  
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0), 
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.55),
        plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 2.9),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 6.5)) +
     labs(x = "", 
          y = "", 
          fill = "Correlation between\nnew license applications per\ncommunity area by\nbusiness activity \n\n(The darker the color of the cell, the more \nsimilar were location choices of firms in\nintersecting industries in Chicago in 2018)",
       title = "\nBusiness services, creative, food, luxury firms move together",
       subtitle = "So do retail, beauty, and home repair and cleaning services. Manufacturing \nand hospitals have different location patterns from most other businesses\n",
       caption = "Source: Business Licenses - Chicago Data Portal, City of Chicago"))

ggsave("tiles_corr_by_industry.png", height = 7, width = 8)

The heat map above reveals location decision patterns in Chicago that could help us think about economic development in geographical dimensions. In 2018, we can see a high correlation in the data between new business licenses for creative industry firms (e.g. art, music, publishing, advertising), business services firms (e.g. consulting, accounting, staffing), and luxury firms (jewerly and antique stores, travel agencies) decisions to locate in certain community areas. Importantly, the correlation was high on average and close across most of industry pairs - meaning that certain areas must be popular among firms dealing with all kinds of business. The only exceptions from the rule were manufacturing and medical firms that had way lower correlation coefficients for their location decisions, when paired with other firms.
